drug.name: Brolucizumab
drug.description:
Brolucizumab, also known as RTH258 or ESBA1008,[A187211] is a monoclonal antibody indicated to treat neovascular age related macular degeneration.[L9089]
Brolucizumab was granted FDA approval in October 2019.[L9089]

drug.indication: Brolucizumab is a monoclonal antibody indicated to treat neovascular age related macular degeneration.[A187208,L9089]
drug.pharmacodynamics: Brolucizumab is a vascular endothelial growth factor (VEGF) inhibitor which reduces proliferation of endothelial cells, vascularization of the tissue, and permeability of the vasculature.[L9089] It has a long duration of action as it is given monthly.[L9089] Patients should be counselled regarding the risk of endophthalmitis, retinal detachment, and arterial thromboembolic events following administration of this medication.[L9089]
drug.mechanism-of-action: Brolucizumab is a vascular endothelial growth factor (VEGF) inhibitor which targets the major VEGF-A isoforms: VEGF<sub>110</sub>, VEGF<sub>121</sub>, and VEGF<sub>165</sub>.[A187196,A187208,L9089] Inhibition of these VEGF-A isoforms reduce proliferation of endothelial cells, vascularization of the tissue, and permeability of the vasculature.[L9089]
drug.toxicity: Data regarding the toxicity of brolucizumab is not readily available.[L9089]
drug.metabolism: Monoclonal antibodies are expected to undergo proteolysis to smaller peptides and amino acids.[A31470]
drug.absorption: A 3mg dose of brolucizumab reaches a C<sub>max</sub> of 20.7ng/mL with a T<sub>max</sub> of 20.3h and an AUC of 2480ng\*h/mL.[L9104] A 6mg dose of brolucizumab reaches a C<sub>max</sub> of 77.6ng/mL with a T<sub>max</sub> of 17.4h and an AUC of 9169ng\*h/mL.[L9104]
drug.half-life: The systemic half life of bolucizumab is 4.4Â±2.0 days.[L9089] The elimination half life is 108h for a 3mg dose and 103h for a 6mg dose.[L9104]
drug.protein-binding: Monoclonal antibodies are generally not protein bound in serum.[A31470]
drug.route-of-elimination: Data regarding the route of elimination is not readily available.[L9089] Monoclonal antibodies are generally not eliminated in the urine, and only a small amount is excreted in bile.[A40006]
drug.volume-of-distribution: Data regarding the volume of distribution is not readily available.[L9089]
drug.clearance: Data regarding the clearance of brolucizumab is not readily available.[L9089]

polypeptide.name: Vascular endothelial growth factor A
polypeptide.general-function: Vascular endothelial growth factor receptor binding
polypeptide.specific-function: Growth factor active in angiogenesis, vasculogenesis and endothelial cell growth. Induces endothelial cell proliferation, promotes cell migration, inhibits apoptosis and induces permeabilization of blood vessels. Binds to the FLT1/VEGFR1 and KDR/VEGFR2 receptors, heparan sulfate and heparin. NRP1/Neuropilin-1 binds isoforms VEGF-165 and VEGF-145. Isoform VEGF165B binds to KDR but does not activate downstream signaling pathways, does not activate angiogenesis and inhibits tumor growth.
